# Coding Rules for CMTI Order Management Project

## Project Context
- React 18+ with functional components and hooks
- Ant Design (antd) as the primary UI component library
- Tailwind CSS for utility styling alongside Ant Design
- Custom CSS in App.css for global styles
- DayJS for date manipulation
- XLSX for Excel export functionality

## File Structure & Imports

### Import Order (strict)
1. React hooks from 'react'
2. Third-party icons from '@ant-design/icons'
3. Ant Design components from 'antd'
4. Third-party libraries (dayjs, xlsx, etc.)
5. Local configuration imports (API_BASE_URL, date utilities)
6. Local CSS files (App.css)

### Example:
```jsx
import { useCallback, useEffect, useMemo, useState } from 'react'
import {
  PlusOutlined,
  SearchOutlined,
  EyeOutlined,
} from '@ant-design/icons'
import {
  Button,
  Form,
  Input,
  Modal,
  Table,
  message,
} from 'antd'
import dayjs from 'dayjs'
import '../App.css'
import { API_BASE_URL } from '../config/api.js'
import { DISPLAY_DATE_FORMAT, formatDate } from '../config/date.js'
```

## Naming Conventions

- **Components**: PascalCase (e.g., `Proposals`, `MasterProposalsTable`)
- **Functions**: camelCase (e.g., `fetchProposals`, `handleSubmit`)
- **Constants**: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (e.g., `PROPOSAL_FIELDS`, `API_BASE_URL`)
- **State Variables**: camelCase with descriptive names (e.g., `tableData`, `loading`)
- **Boolean States**: Prefix with is/has/should (e.g., `isModalOpen`, `hasData`)
- **Event Handlers**: Prefix with handle (e.g., `handleSubmit`, `handleClose`)
- **Modal Open States**: Suffix with `Open` or `Visible` (e.g., `modalOpen`, `docsModalVisible`)

## React Hooks Usage

### useState
- Group related state together when logical
- Initialize with proper default values
- Use descriptive names

```jsx
const [tableData, setTableData] = useState([])
const [filteredData, setFilteredData] = useState([])
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false)
const [modalOpen, setModalOpen] = useState(false)
```

### useCallback
- ALWAYS wrap all functions with useCallback
- Include all dependencies in the dependency array
- Use for event handlers, API calls, and memoized functions

```jsx
const fetchProposals = useCallback(async () => {
  setLoading(true)
  try {
    const response = await fetch(`${API_BASE_URL}/proposals/`)
    // ... logic
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error)
    message.error('Error message')
  } finally {
    setLoading(false)
  }
}, [/* dependencies */])
```

### useEffect
- Use for side effects only
- Include all dependencies
- Clean up subscriptions/event listeners

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  fetchProposals()
  fetchStats()
  fetchStageConfig()
}, [fetchProposals, fetchStats, fetchStageConfig])
```

### useMemo
- Use for expensive computations
- Use for derived data that doesn't need to change on every render

```jsx
const statistics = useMemo(() => {
  const total = tableData.length
  const completed = tableData.filter(item => item.status === 'completed').length
  return { total, completed }
}, [tableData])
```

## API & Data Fetching

### Fetch Pattern
- Always use async/await
- Use try/catch/finally blocks
- Set loading states appropriately
- Handle errors with user feedback
- Use proper headers: `{ accept: 'application/json' }`

```jsx
const fetchData = useCallback(async () => {
  setLoading(true)
  try {
    const response = await fetch(`${API_BASE_URL}/endpoint/`, {
      headers: { accept: 'application/json' },
    })
    if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Failed to fetch')
    const data = await response.json()
    setTableData(Array.isArray(data) ? data : [])
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching data:', error)
    message.error(error.message || 'Unable to fetch data')
    setTableData([])
  } finally {
    setLoading(false)
  }
}, [])
```

### Data Mapping
- Create mapper functions for API to UI conversion
- Handle edge cases (null, undefined, empty arrays)

```jsx
const mapApiToUi = (record) => ({
  id: record?.id ?? '',
  name: record?.name ?? '',
  key: record?.id ?? crypto.randomUUID(),
})
```

## UI Components

### Table Columns Definition
- Define columns as arrays of objects
- Include width for each column
- Use fixed: 'left' or fixed: 'right' for important columns
- Use render functions for custom cell content

```jsx
const columns = [
  { 
    title: 'Name', 
    dataIndex: 'name', 
    key: 'name', 
    width: 200,
    fixed: 'left',
    render: (value) => value || '-'
  },
  {
    title: 'Status',
    dataIndex: 'status',
    key: 'status',
    width: 120,
    render: (value) => value ? <Tag color="blue">{value}</Tag> : null,
  },
]
```

### Modal Usage
- Use `open` prop (not `visible` - deprecated)
- Include maskClosable={false} for important modals
- Provide proper footer buttons or footer={null}
- Set appropriate width

```jsx
<Modal
  title="Modal Title"
  open={modalOpen}
  onCancel={closeModal}
  footer={[
    <Button key="cancel" onClick={closeModal}>Cancel</Button>,
    <Button key="submit" type="primary" onClick={handleSubmit}>Submit</Button>,
  ]}
  width={700}
  maskClosable={false}
>
  {/* Content */}
</Modal>
```

### Form Handling
- Use Form.useForm() hook
- Set initial values with form.setFieldsValue()
- Reset form on modal close
- Add validation rules

```jsx
const [form] = Form.useForm()

const openEditModal = useCallback((record) => {
  form.resetFields()
  form.setFieldsValue(record)
  setModalOpen(true)
}, [form])

// In JSX
<Form form={form} onFinish={handleSubmit}>
  <Form.Item 
    name="fieldName" 
    label="Field Label"
    rules={[{ required: true, message: 'Field is required' }]}
  >
    <Input />
  </Form.Item>
</Form>
```

## Error Handling

- Always wrap async operations in try/catch
- Log errors to console for debugging
- Show user-friendly error messages
- Gracefully handle empty/null data

```jsx
try {
  // async operation
} catch (error) {
  console.error('Descriptive error message:', error)
  message.error(error.message || 'User-friendly error message')
} finally {
  // cleanup (set loading false, etc.)
}
```

## Date Handling

- Use dayjs for all date operations
- Use formatDate utility for display
- Use DISPLAY_DATE_FORMAT constant

```jsx
import dayjs from 'dayjs'
import { formatDate, DISPLAY_DATE_FORMAT } from '../config/date.js'

// Display
render: (value) => formatDate(value) || '-'

// DatePicker
<DatePicker format="DD.MM.YYYY" />

// DayJS operations
const date = dayjs(value)
const isValid = date.isSameOrAfter(dayjs())
```

## Styling

- Use Tailwind utility classes where possible
- Use Ant Design's built-in styling props
- Use inline styles sparingly for dynamic values
- Consistent spacing with Tailwind (p-4, m-2, gap-4, etc.)

```jsx
// Good - Tailwind
<div className="flex items-center gap-4 p-4">

// Good - Ant Design props
<Card size="small" className="shadow-md">
<Button type="primary" size="small">

// Acceptable - Inline for dynamic
<span style={{ color: count > 0 ? 'green' : 'red' }}>
```

## LocalStorage Usage

- Always wrap in try/catch
- Parse JSON safely
- Handle missing data gracefully

```jsx
try {
  const rawUser = window.localStorage.getItem('ppm_user')
  if (rawUser) {
    const parsedUser = JSON.parse(rawUser)
    setCurrentUserName(parsedUser.name)
  }
} catch (storageError) {
  console.error('Failed to read from localStorage', storageError)
}
```

## Code Organization

### Component Structure
1. Imports
2. Constants (field definitions, options arrays)
3. Helper functions (mappers, formatters)
4. Main component function
5. State declarations
6. Callback functions (useCallback)
7. Effects (useEffect)
8. Derived data (useMemo)
9. JSX return

### Field Definitions
- Define field configurations as constants at the top
- Include name, label, width, and optional properties

```jsx
const PROPOSAL_FIELDS = [
  { name: 'id', label: 'SL NO', width: 120, fixed: 'left' },
  { name: 'customer_name', label: 'Customer Name', width: 170 },
  { 
    name: 'status', 
    label: 'Status', 
    width: 150, 
    input: 'select',
    render: (value) => value ? <Tag color="blue">{value}</Tag> : null
  },
]
```

## Critical Rules

### MUST DO
- ✅ ALWAYS use useCallback for every function
- ✅ ALWAYS include all dependencies in useCallback/useEffect
- ✅ ALWAYS handle loading states for async operations
- ✅ ALWAYS show error messages to users via antd message
- ✅ ALWAYS wrap localStorage access in try/catch
- ✅ ALWAYS use proper key props in lists (rowKey for tables)
- ✅ ALWAYS set scroll={{ x: 'max-content', y: height }} for tables
- ✅ ALWAYS use `open` instead of `visible` for Modal

### NEVER DO
- ❌ NEVER define functions inside render without useCallback
- ❌ NEVER mutate state directly (always use setter functions)
- ❌ NEVER use any type implicitly - be explicit with types or JSDoc
- ❌ NEVER leave console.log in production code (remove or use console.error for errors)
- ❌ NEVER use var - always use const or let
- ❌ NEVER forget to handle the finally block for loading states

## Common Patterns

### Document Count Feature
When adding enquiry documents column to tables:

1. Add state variables for modal and loading
2. Fetch document counts with proposals
3. Add column with View (count) button or "No documents" text
4. Include document modals at end of component

### Table with Horizontal Scroll
```jsx
<Table
  columns={columns}
  scroll={{ x: 'max-content', y: 600 }}
  bordered
  sticky
/>
```

### Conditional Rendering
```jsx
{loading && <Spin />}
{!loading && data.length === 0 && <Empty />}
{!loading && data.length > 0 && <Table dataSource={data} />}
```

### Modal Form Pattern
```jsx
const openModal = useCallback((record) => {
  setEditingRecord(record)
  form.resetFields()
  form.setFieldsValue(record)
  setModalOpen(true)
}, [form])

const closeModal = useCallback(() => {
  setModalOpen(false)
  setEditingRecord(null)
  form.resetFields()
}, [form])
```
